The first step is straightforward partial differentiation. Take the
derivative of $f$ with respect to $x$, treating $y$ as a relative
constant (use the chain rule):

\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial x}((1 - x)y)\right)e^{(1 - x)y} = -ye^{(1 - x)y}.
\end{align*}
Now we just substitute $(x,y) = (2,1)$:

\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}(2,1) &= -1e^{(1 - 2)1} \\ &= -e^{-1}
\end{align*}

